04999nam a22007935i 9781442674721DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426747217 a10.3138/97814426747212doi  a(DE-B1597)464463  a(OCoLC)1013958044  a(OCoLC)944178069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR428.E95bK35 2003 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a820.9/372221 aKallendorf, Hilaire, eauthor.10aExorcism and Its Texts :bSubjectivity in Early Modern Literature of England and Spain /cHilaire Kallendorf. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2003  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUniversity of Toronto Romance Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue - A Force Within: The Importance of Demonic Possession for Early Modern Studies -- tA Paradigm of Theologemes for Literary Exorcism -- tIntroduction: The Morphology of Exorcism, or a Grammar of Possession in Spanish and English Literature, 1550-1700 -- t1. Demoniacs in the Drama: Theatricalities of Comic Possession and the Exorcism of the Body Politic -- t2. Possessed Pícaros and Satanic Satire -- t3. Romance, the Interlude, and Hagiographical Drama: The Humanization of Possession and Exorcism -- t4. Tragedy As the Absence or Failure of Exorcism -- t5. Self-Exorcism and the Rise of the Novel -- tConclusion: Liturgy in Literature, or Early Modern Literary Theory and the Christian Legitimate Marvellous -- tEpilogue: Problematizing the Category of 'Demonic Possession -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExorcism and demonic possession appear as recurrent motifs in early modern Spanish and English literatures. In Exorcism and Its Texts, Hilaire Kallendorf demonstrates how this 'infection' was represented in some thirty works of literature by fifteen different authors, ranging from canonical classics like Shakespeare, Cervantes, Ben Jonson, and Lope de Vega, to obscure works by anonymous writers. From comic and tragic drama to picaresque narrative and eight other genres, possession worked as a paradigm through which authors could convey extraordinary experience, including not only demonic possession but also madness or even murder. The devil was thought to be able to enter the bodily organs and infect memory, imagination, and reason. Some came to believe that possession was tied to enthusiasm, poetic frenzy, prophecy, and genius. Authors often drew upon sensational details of actual exorcisms. In some cases, such as in Shakespeare, curing the body (and the body politic) meant affirming cultural authority; in others, as with Zamora, it clearly meant subverting it. Drawing on the disciplines of literary theory and history, Exorcism and its Texts is the first comprehensive study of this compelling topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aComparative literaturexEnglish and Spanish. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aExorcism in literature. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442674721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442674721.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  